","workspace_file_chunks":[]},{"status":"success","request_id":"b863d652-f2ad-4e93-81a8-6fd1e71fd7a0","request_message":"","structured_output_nodes":[{"id":1,"type":5,"content":"","tool_use":{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CsZfzNuP2McsfxwyLu7myX","tool_name":"sequentialthinking_Sequential_thinking","input_json":"{"thought": "Let me think about the best approach for the implementation:\n\nOption 1: Filter players before calling findAndTeleportPlayers()\n- Pros: Clean separation, prevents unnecessary location finding if no one can teleport\n- Cons: Might need to handle edge cases where all players are in combat\n\nOption 2: Check combat status in teleportPlayersToLocation()\n- Pros: More granular control, can provide individual feedback\n- Cons: Might waste resources finding a location when no one can teleport\n\nI think Option 1 is better, but I should also add a check in teleportPlayersToLocation() as a safety measure.\n\nImplementation Plan:\n1. Add CombatLogX dependencies\n2. Create CombatLogXIntegration class with methods:\n - isEnabled() - check if CombatLogX is available\n - isInCombat(Player) - check if specific player is in combat\n - filterPlayersNotInCombat(Set<UUID>) - filter out players in combat\n3. Modify PortalRTPTask to use the integration\n4. Add configuration option to enable/disable this feature\n5. Add messaging to inform players why they weren't teleported", "nextThoughtNeeded": true, "thoughtNumber": 2, "totalThoughts": 3}","mcp_server_name":"Sequential_thinking","mcp_tool_name":"sequentialthinking"}},{"id":2,"type":0,"content":""},{"id":3,"type":2,"content":""},{"id":4,"type":3,"content":""}],"seen_state":"seen","structured_request_nodes":[{"id":1,"type":1,"tool_result_node":{"content":"{
